## ❗ Problem Being Solved

Background artists in a typical 2D animation studio spend an average of 8 hours per background manually painting detailed environments from scratch.

In a mid-sized studio producing 20 episodes per season with an average of 12 unique backgrounds per episode, this generates ~1,920 hours of repetitive detailing work per season — for one studio alone.
**Pain points addressed:**
- Implied locations buried in action lines missed during manual reads
- Mood and atmosphere notes inconsistently captured across supervisors
- No standardised format — every supervisor extracts differently
- New artists can't independently interpret vague scene directions
---

## ⚡ Automation Potential

**Level: High**

| Dimension | Assessment |
|-----------|------------|
| Repetitiveness | Triggered for every new episode script and every revision |
| Data availability | Script readily available from production coordinator |
| Human judgment needed | Supervisor confirms complexity ratings — especially for visually complex scenes |
| Integration possibility | Output can feed directly into Shotgrid or Notion production tracker |
| Estimated time saving | ~75% — from 45–90 min to 10–15 min per episode |

**Human-in-the-loop role:** Supervisor reviews extracted list, confirms complexity ratings and approves before passing to P02.

---

## ⚠️ Risks and Limitations

| Risk | Level | Mitigation |
|------|-------|------------|
| AI misses implied locations  | Medium | Prompt instructs AI to flag unclear or underdescribed scenes |
| Mood hallucinated where not stated | Medium | Prompt uses "if specified or implied" — uncertain fields flagged not assumed |
| Complexity rated incorrectly without storyboard reference  | Medium | Supervisor confirms all complexity ratings before list enters P02 |
| Long scripts processed in one pass may produce inconsistent extraction | Low | Process in scene blocks (e.g. 10 scenes at a time) not full episode at once |

**Overall risk rating: MEDIUM** — all outputs reviewed by supervisor before entering pipeline.

